3. How to call Power Apps to Power Automate:-

In my experience, we can call Power Automate from Power Apps by creating an instant cloud flow with the Power Apps trigger. 
First, I create a flow in Power Automate and select the 'Power Apps' trigger. 
Then I define the required input parameters such as ID, name, or any field that I want to pass from Power Apps. 
After creating the flow logic, like sending an email or updating Dataverse, I save the flow.

Then in Power Apps, I connect the flow using the Power Automate option and call it using the FlowName.Run() function. 
For example, when a user clicks a Submit button, I call the flow and pass the required parameters. 
This way, Power Apps triggers Power Automate to perform background operations like approvals, notifications.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

4. Explain real-time challenges you faced while developing an app and how you overcame them?

I have faced a some of real challenges:

â€” While developing the export-to-Excel functionality in my application, 
one of the main challenges I faced was handling large datasets and data formatting issues. 
Business users wanted to export filtered records from a Gallery directly into Excel, but Power Apps does not have a built-in feature to generate Excel files. 
Initially, when I tried passing the entire collection to Power Automate, the flow performance was slow, and sometimes it failed due to payload size limits.

â€” In my project,
when users wanted to export Gallery data to Excel, I handled it using Power Apps and Power Automate together. 
When the user clicks the Export button, I pass the Gallery data to Power Automate in JSON format using the JSON function.
I use ShowColumns to send only the required fields instead of all columns, which improves performance. (ShowColumns(EmployeeList, "EmployeeName", "EmployeeID"))
Now in Power Automate, the data is received as a JSON string, so the first thing I do is use the Parse JSON action.
This step is very important because it converts the JSON text into structured data so I can access individual fields.
Then I use the Create CSV table action to generate the file. 
After that, I use the Create file action in SharePoint or OneDrive for Busines to store the file.
Finally, I generate a shareable link and send it back in power apps so that user can download the Excel file. 

â€” Another challenge was handling date and number format conversions, 
so I implemented proper formatting expressions and added error handling using Scopes and Configure Run After. 
After implementing these improvements, the export process became stable, faster, and more reliable for users.

â€” One more challenge i was faced Delegation,
when I connected my app to a SharePoint list with thousands of items, only 500 records were loading due to delegation limits.
At first, it was really frustrating because users needed full data.
What I did was optimize my formulas with delegable functions like StartsWith() and Filter().
And in some cases where delegation still didnâ€™t work, I called a Power Automate flow from the app to fetch only the required records. 
